children.subject: I don't think it's recommended by the department, but in my opinion you can do 170 without 70 if you brush up on the proofs taught in the first few lectures. CS188 had a significant probability component to it, so unless you're already comfortable with that from prior experience, I'd recommend against taking it.
Same question but what if I took 61 series but not cs70?

history.content:
I'm in 188 and I have taken 170 previously.  First off, no class actually enforces prerequisites.  That being said, I found 170 to be pretty challenging even after taking 70.  If you are good at mathematical proofs and have a good foundation in probability theory you will be able to take 170 - this is essentially what is taught in 70.  It is fine to take without the 61 series since it does not really deal with anything directly related to programming or data structures except for a basic understanding of recursion.  You do discuss some algorithms that are covered in 61 series but whether you feel comfortable enough to cover the basics of those yourself is up to you. 

For 188 it is slightly different.  It assumes you have a strong programming foundation and a good grasp of the material taught in 61a/b, especially data structures.  The mathematics used in 188 trend towards probability theory (like Markov Chains) and a few other topics.  I would recommend taking 188 if you feel you have a strong grasp of python, data structures, and core topics in probability.  For reference, I feel the most important classes to have for 188 are 61a, 61b, and 70 - that's my personal opinion though.
